WEBVTT

00:22.680 --> 00:25.480
CHAPTER XXI.

00:30.660 --> 00:34.840
Let me put down with exactness all that happened, as well as I can remember,

00:34.980 --> 00:39.640
since last I made an entry. Not a detail that I can recall must be forgotten,

00:39.940 --> 00:45.580
in whole calmness I must proceed. When I came to Renfield's room I found him lying on the floor,

00:45.660 --> 00:50.780
on his left side, in a glittering pool of blood. When I went to move him it became at once apparent

00:50.780 --> 00:55.860
that he had received some terrible injuries. There seemed none of the unity of purpose between the

00:55.860 --> 01:02.840
which marks even lethargic sanity. As the face was exposed I could see that it was horribly bruised,

01:03.020 --> 01:07.740
as though it had been beaten against the floor. Indeed, it was from the face wounds that the pool

01:07.740 --> 01:14.120
of blood originated. The attendant who was kneeling beside the body said to me as we turned him over,

01:14.580 --> 01:19.600
I think, sir, his back is broken. See, both his right arm and leg and the whole side of his face

01:19.600 --> 01:24.600
are paralyzed. How such a thing could have happened puzzled the attendant beyond measure.

01:24.600 --> 01:28.460
He seemed quite bewildered and his brows were gathered in as he said,

01:28.920 --> 01:33.720
I can't understand the two things. He could mark his face like that by beating his own head on the

01:33.720 --> 01:38.560
floor. I saw a young woman do it once at the Eversfield Asylum before anyone could lay hands

01:38.560 --> 01:43.560
on her. And I suppose he might have broken his neck by falling out of bed if he got in an awkward

01:43.560 --> 01:49.380
kink. But for the life of me I can't imagine how the two things occurred. If his back was broke

01:49.380 --> 01:53.580
he couldn't beat his head. And if his face was like that before the fall out of bed there would

01:53.580 --> 02:00.060
be marks on it. I said to him, go to Dr. Van Helsing and ask him to kindly come here at once.

02:00.260 --> 02:06.180
I want him without an instant's delay. The man ran off and within a few minutes the

02:06.180 --> 02:10.680
professor in his dressing gown and slippers appeared. When he saw Renfield on the ground

02:10.680 --> 02:15.940
he looked keenly at him a moment then turned to me. I think he recognized my thought in my eyes

02:15.940 --> 02:21.620
for he said very quietly manifestly for the ears of the attendant. Ah, a sad accident.

02:22.180 --> 02:27.020
He will need very careful watching and much attention. I shall stay with you myself,

02:27.240 --> 02:32.100
but I shall first dress myself. If you will remain I shall in a few minutes join you.

02:33.180 --> 02:37.800
The patient was now breathing stertoriously and it was easy to see that he had suffered some

02:37.800 --> 02:43.480
terrible injury. Van Helsing returned with extraordinary celerity bearing with him a

02:43.480 --> 02:49.000
surgical case. He had evidently been thinking and had his mind made up for almost before he looked

02:49.000 --> 02:54.620
the patient he whispered to me, send the attendant away. We must be alone with him when he becomes

02:54.620 --> 03:01.020
conscious after the operation. I said, I think that will do now Simmons. We have done all that

03:01.020 --> 03:06.040
we can at present. You had better go your round and Dr. Van Helsing will operate. Let me know

03:06.040 --> 03:12.520
instantly if there be anything unusual anywhere. The man withdrew and we went into a strict

03:12.520 --> 03:18.600
examination of the patient. The wounds of the face were superficial. The real injury was at

03:18.600 --> 03:25.500
the pressed fracture of the skull extending right up through the motor area. The professor thought a

03:25.500 --> 03:30.880
moment and said, we must reduce the pressure and get back to normal conditions as far as can be.

03:31.500 --> 03:37.120
The rapidity of the suffusion shows the terrible nature of his injury. The whole motor area seems

03:37.120 --> 03:46.660
affected. The suffusion of the brain will increase quickly so he must cleft in at once or it may be

03:46.660 --> 03:52.020
tapping at the door. I went over and opened it and found in the corridor without Arthur and

03:52.020 --> 03:57.780
Quincy in pajamas and slippers. The former spoke, I heard your man call up Dr. Van Helsing and tell

03:57.780 --> 04:03.160
him of an accident. So I woke Quincy or rather called for him as he was not asleep. Things are

04:03.160 --> 04:08.500
moving too quickly and too strangely for sound sleep for any of us these times. I've been thinking

04:08.500 --> 04:13.140
that tomorrow night we'll not see things as they have been. We'll have to look back and forward a

04:13.140 --> 04:18.920
little more than we have done. May we come in? I nodded and held the door open till they had entered

04:18.920 --> 04:24.240
then I closed it again. When Quincy saw the attitude and state of the patient and noted the

04:24.240 --> 04:29.760
horrible pool on the floor he said softly, my God, what has happened to him? Poor, poor devil.

04:30.860 --> 04:36.440
I told him briefly and added that we expected he would recover consciousness after the operation

04:36.440 --> 04:41.640
for a short time at all events. He went at once and sat down on the edge of the bed with

04:41.640 --> 04:47.260
a dollaming beside him. We all watched in patience. We shall wait, said Van Helsing,

04:47.600 --> 04:51.800
just long enough to fix the best spot for roughening so that we may most quickly and

04:51.800 --> 04:55.840
perfectly remove the blood clot for it is evident that the hemorrhage is increasing.

04:57.320 --> 05:02.560
The minutes during which we waited passed with fearful slowness. I had a horrible sinking in my

05:02.560 --> 05:07.380
heart and from Van Helsing's face I gathered that he felt some fear or apprehension as to what was

05:07.380 --> 05:12.580
to come. I dreaded the words Renfield might speak. I was positively afraid to think.

05:13.240 --> 05:17.900
But the conviction of what was coming was on me as I have read of men who have heard the death watch.

05:18.540 --> 05:23.220
The poor man's breathing came in uncertain gasps. Each instant he seemed as though he would open

05:23.220 --> 05:28.020
his eyes and speak but then would follow a prolonged stertorous breath and he would relapse

05:28.020 --> 05:34.180
into a more fixed insensibility. Inured as I was to sickbeds and death the suspense grew and grew

05:34.180 --> 05:38.700
upon me. I could almost hear the beating of my own heart and the blood surging through my

05:38.700 --> 05:45.180
temple sounded like blows from a hammer. Silence finally became agonizing. I looked at my companions

05:45.180 --> 05:49.840
one after another and saw from their flushed faces and damp brows that they were enduring equal

05:49.840 --> 05:55.260
torture. There was a nervous suspense over us all as though overhead some dread bell would

05:55.260 --> 06:02.200
peel out powerfully when we should least expect it. At last there came a time when it was evident

06:02.200 --> 06:07.320
the patient was sinking fast. He might die at any moment. I looked up at the professor and

06:07.320 --> 06:12.700
caught his eyes fixed on mine. His face was sternly sad as he spoke. That is no time to lose.

06:13.180 --> 06:16.920
His words may be worth many lives. I have been thinking so as I stood here.

06:17.180 --> 06:21.340
It may be there is a soul at stake. We shall operate just above the ear.

06:22.780 --> 06:27.600
Without another word he made the operation. For a few moments the breathing continued to be

06:27.600 --> 06:32.560
then there came a breath so prolonged that it seemed as though it would tear open his chest.

06:33.040 --> 06:38.080
Suddenly his eyes opened and became fixed in a wild helpless stare. This was continued for a

06:38.080 --> 06:42.920
few moments then it was softened into a glad surprise and from his lips came a sigh of relief.

06:43.620 --> 06:49.960
He moved convulsively and as he did so said I'll be quiet doctor tell them to take off the straight

06:49.960 --> 06:55.460
waistcoat. I have had a terrible dream and it has left me so weak that I cannot move.

06:55.460 --> 06:59.680
What's wrong with my face? It feels all swollen and it smarts dreadfully.

07:00.840 --> 07:04.920
He tried to turn his head but even with the effort his eyes seemed to grow glassy again so

07:04.920 --> 07:12.000
I gently put it back. Then Van Helsing said in a quiet gray voice. Tell us your dream Mr. Renfield.

07:13.700 --> 07:17.300
As he heard the voice his face brightened through its mutilation and he said.

07:18.000 --> 07:24.320
That is Dr. Van Helsing. How good it is of you to be here. Give me some water. My lips are dry

07:24.320 --> 07:30.720
and I shall try to tell you. I dreamed. He stopped and seemed fainting. I called quietly to Quincy.

07:30.860 --> 07:35.820
The brandy. It is in my study. Quick. He flew and returned to the glass. The decanter of brandy

07:35.820 --> 07:41.340
and a carafe of water. We moistened the parts lips and the patient quickly revived. It seemed

07:41.340 --> 07:45.700
however that his poor injured brain had been working in the interval for when he was quite

07:45.700 --> 07:50.240
conscious he looked at me piercingly with an agonized confusion which I shall never forget

07:50.240 --> 07:57.060
and said I must not deceive myself it was no dream but all a grim reality

07:57.640 --> 08:02.500
then his eyes roved around the room as they caught sight of the two figures sitting patiently on the

08:02.500 --> 08:08.540
edge of the bed he went on if I were not sure already I would know from them for an instant

08:08.540 --> 08:13.800
his eyes closed not with pain or sleep but voluntarily as though he were bringing all his

08:13.800 --> 08:19.300
faculties to bear when he opened them he said hurriedly and with more energy than he had yet

08:19.300 --> 08:25.000
displayed quick doctor quick I am dying I feel that I have but a few minutes and then I must go

08:25.000 --> 08:31.300
back to death or worse wet my lips with brandy again I have something that I must say before I

08:31.300 --> 08:37.940
die or before my crushed brain dies anyhow thank you it was that night after you left me when I

08:37.940 --> 08:47.680
implored you to let me go away I couldn't speak then for I felt my tongue was tied but I was as

08:47.680 --> 08:53.460
despair for a long time after you left me it seemed hours then there came a sudden peace to

08:53.460 --> 08:58.540
me my brain seemed to become cool again and I realized where I was I heard the dogs bark

08:58.540 --> 09:05.800
behind our house but not where he was as he spoke Van Helsing's eyes never blinked but his hand came

09:05.800 --> 09:11.700
out and met mine and gripped it hard he did not however betray himself he nodded slightly and said

09:11.700 --> 09:13.640
gone in a low voice

09:15.760 --> 09:21.460
Renfield proceeded he came up to the window in the mist as I had seen him often before but he

09:21.460 --> 09:26.520
was solid then not a ghost and his eyes were fierce like a man's when angry he was laughing

09:26.520 --> 09:30.940
with his red mouth the sharp white teeth glinted in the moonlight when he turned to look back over

09:30.940 --> 09:35.960
the belt of trees to where the dogs were barking I wouldn't ask him to come in at first though I knew

09:35.960 --> 09:42.220
he wanted to just as he had wanted all along then he began promising me things not in words but by

09:42.220 --> 09:50.160
doing them he was interrupted by a word from the professor how by making them happen just as he

09:50.160 --> 09:55.600
used to send in the flies when the sun was shining great big fat ones with steel and sapphire on their

09:55.600 --> 10:01.640
wings and big moths in the night with skull and crossbones on their backs Van Helsing nodded to

10:01.640 --> 10:06.660
him and he whispered to me unconsciously the acarantia atropos of the sphinges what you call

10:06.660 --> 10:14.400
the death's head moth the patient went on without stopping then he began to whisper rats rats rats

10:14.400 --> 10:20.620
hundreds thousands millions of them and everyone in life and dogs to eat them and cats too all

10:20.620 --> 10:26.300
lives all red blood with years of life in it and not merely buzzing flies I laughed at him for I

10:26.300 --> 10:31.940
wanted to see what he could do then the dogs howled away beyond the dark trees in his house

10:31.940 --> 10:37.480
he beckoned me to the window I got up and looked out and he raised his hands and seemed to call out

10:37.480 --> 10:43.140
without using any words a dark mass spread over the grass coming on like the shape of a flame of

10:43.140 --> 10:48.800
fire and then he moved the mist to the right and left and I could see that there were thousands of

10:48.800 --> 10:54.500
rats with their eyes blazing red like his only smaller he held up his hand and they all stopped

10:54.500 --> 11:00.160
and I thought he seemed to be saying all these lies will I give you I am many more and greater

11:00.160 --> 11:06.240
through countless ages if you will fall down and worship me and then a red cloud like the color of

11:06.240 --> 11:11.100
blood seemed to close over my eyes and before I knew what I was doing I found myself opening

11:11.100 --> 11:17.860
the sash and saying to him come in lord and master the rats were all gone but he slid into the room

11:17.860 --> 11:23.500
through the sash though it was only open an inch wide just as the moon herself has often come in

11:23.500 --> 11:30.800
the tiniest crack and it stood before me in all her size and splendor his voice was weaker so I

11:30.800 --> 11:35.500
moistened his lips with the brandy again and he continued but it seemed as though his memory had

11:35.500 --> 11:40.700
gone on working in the interval for his story was further advanced I was about to call him back to

11:40.700 --> 11:46.620
the point but Van Helsing whispered to me let him go on do not interrupt him he could not go back

11:46.620 --> 11:50.560
and maybe he could not proceed at all if once he lost the thread of his thought

11:51.780 --> 11:57.980
he proceeded all day I waited to hear from him but he did not send me anything not even a blow

11:57.980 --> 12:03.640
fly and when the moon got up I was pretty angry with him when he did slide into the window though

12:03.640 --> 12:09.140
it was shut and did not even knock I got mad with him he sneered at me and his white face looked out

12:09.140 --> 12:14.160
of the mist with his red eyes gleaming and he went on as though he owned the whole place and I was

12:14.160 --> 12:18.700
he didn't even smell the same as he went by me I couldn't hold him

12:18.700 --> 12:24.120
I thought that somehow Mrs. Harker had come into the room the two men sitting on the bed stood up

12:24.120 --> 12:28.580
and came over standing behind him so that he could not see them but where they could hear better

12:28.580 --> 12:34.100
they were both silent but the professor started and quivered his face however grew grimmer and

12:34.100 --> 12:40.100
sterner still Renfield went on without noticing when Mrs. Harker came in to see me this afternoon

12:40.100 --> 12:45.920
she wasn't the same it was like tea after the teapot has been watered here we all moved but

12:45.920 --> 12:52.120
no one said a word he went on I didn't know that she was here till she spoke and she didn't look

12:52.120 --> 12:57.620
the same I don't care for the pale people I like them with lots of blood in them and hers all seem

12:57.620 --> 13:03.160
to have run out I didn't think of it at the time but when she went away I began to think and it

13:03.160 --> 13:08.360
made me mad to know that he had been taking the life out of her I could feel that the rest quivered

13:08.360 --> 13:15.180
as I did but we remained otherwise still so when he came tonight I was ready for him I saw the mist

13:15.180 --> 13:20.280
stealing in and I grabbed it tight I had heard that madmen have unnatural strength and as I knew

13:20.280 --> 13:27.160
I was a madman at times anyhow I resolved to use my power and he felt it too for he had to come out

13:27.160 --> 13:31.980
of the mist to struggle with me I held tight and I thought I was going to win for I didn't mean him

13:31.980 --> 13:37.480
to take any more of her life till I saw his eyes they burned into me and my strength became like

13:37.480 --> 13:42.620
water he slipped through it and when I tried to cling to him he raised me up and flung me down

13:42.620 --> 13:47.900
there was a red cloud before me and a noise like thunder and the mist seemed to steal away under

13:47.900 --> 13:54.400
the door his voice was becoming fainter and his breath more stertorous Van Helsing stood up

13:54.400 --> 14:01.380
instinctively we know the worst now he said he is here and we know his purpose it may not be too late

14:01.380 --> 14:07.020
let us be armed the same as we were the other night but lose no time there is not an instant to spare

14:08.220 --> 14:13.080
there was no need to put our fear nay our conviction into words we shared them in common

14:13.080 --> 14:17.760
we all hurried and took from our rooms the same things that we had when we entered the count's

14:17.760 --> 14:22.960
house the professor had his ready and as we met in the corridor he pointed to them significantly

14:22.960 --> 14:29.600
as he said they never leave me and they shall not till this unhappy business is over be wise also

14:29.600 --> 14:35.420
my friends it is no common enemy that we deal with alas alas that the amino should suffer

14:36.100 --> 14:41.900
he stopped his voice was breaking and i do not know if rage or terror predominated in my own heart

14:43.420 --> 14:48.140
outside the harker's door we paused artin quincy held back and the latter said

14:48.140 --> 14:54.860
should we disturb her we must said van helsing grimly if the door be locked i shall break it in

14:55.580 --> 15:00.640
may it not frighten her terribly it is unusual to break in to a lady's room

15:00.640 --> 15:06.920
van helsing said solemnly you are always right but this is life and death all chambers are

15:06.920 --> 15:12.960
like to the doctor and even were they not they are all as one to me tonight fringe on when i

15:12.960 --> 15:17.520
turn the handle if the door does not open do you put your shoulder down and shove and you flew my

15:17.520 --> 15:23.660
friends now he turned the handle as he spoke but the door did not yield we threw ourselves against

15:23.660 --> 15:29.100
it with a crash it burst open and we almost fell headlong into the room the professor did actually

15:29.100 --> 15:35.200
fall and i saw across him as he gathered himself up from hands and knees what i saw appalled me i

15:35.200 --> 15:40.660
felt my hair rise like bristles on the back of my neck my heart seemed to stand still the moonlight

15:40.660 --> 15:45.800
was so bright that through the thick yellow blind the room was light enough to see on the bed beside

15:45.800 --> 15:50.820
the window lay jonathan harker his face flushed and breathing heavily as though in a stupor

15:51.540 --> 15:56.240
kneeling on the near edge of the bed facing outwards was the white clad figure of his wife

15:56.240 --> 16:02.020
by her stood a tall thin man clad in black his face was turned from us but the instant we saw

16:02.020 --> 16:07.980
we all recognized the count in every way even to the scar on his forehead with his left hand

16:07.980 --> 16:13.140
he held both mrs harker's hands keeping them away with her arms at full tension his right

16:13.140 --> 16:17.900
hand gripped her by the back of the neck forcing her face down on his bosom her white night dress

16:17.900 --> 16:22.620
was smeared with blood and a thin stream trickled down the man's bare chest which was shown by his

16:22.620 --> 16:28.460
open dress the attitude of the two had a terrible resemblance to a child forcing a kitten's nose

16:28.460 --> 16:34.500
into a saucer of milk to compel it to drink as we burst into the room the count turned his face

16:34.500 --> 16:39.320
and the hellish look that i had heard described seemed to leap into it his eyes flamed red with

16:39.320 --> 16:44.700
devilish passion the great nostrils of the white aquiline nose opened wide and quivered at the edge

16:44.700 --> 16:49.480
and the white sharp teeth behind the full lips of the blood dripping mouth clamped together like

16:49.480 --> 16:54.760
those of a wild beast with a wrench which threw his victim back upon the bed as though hurled from

16:54.760 --> 17:00.900
a height he turned and sprang at us but by this time the professor had gained his feet and was

17:00.900 --> 17:06.500
holding toward him the envelope which contained the sacred wafer the count suddenly stopped just

17:06.500 --> 17:12.120
as poor lucy had done outside the tomb and cowered back further and further back he cowered as we

17:12.120 --> 17:17.600
lifting our crucifixes advanced the moonlight suddenly failed as a great black cloud sailed

17:17.600 --> 17:22.740
across the sky and when the gaslight sprang up under quincy's match we saw nothing but a faint

17:22.740 --> 17:28.420
vapor this as we looked trailed under the door which with the recoil from its bursting open had

17:28.420 --> 17:34.700
swung back to its old position van helsing art and i moved forward to mrs harker who by this time had

17:34.700 --> 17:40.420
drawn her breath and with it had given a scream so wild so ear piercing so despairing that it seems

17:40.420 --> 17:46.220
to me now that it will ring in my ears till my dying day for a few seconds she lay in her helpless

17:46.220 --> 17:52.300
attitude and disarray her face was ghastly with a pallor which was accentuated by the blood which

17:52.300 --> 17:57.660
smeared her lips and cheeks and chin from her throat trickled a thin stream of blood her eyes

17:57.660 --> 18:02.820
were mad with terror then she put before her face her poor crushed hands which bore on their

18:02.820 --> 18:07.660
whiteness the red mark of the count's terrible grip and from behind them came a low desolate

18:07.660 --> 18:12.300
whale which made the terrible scream seem only the quick expression of an endless grief

18:12.960 --> 18:17.260
van helsing stepped forward and drew the coverlet gently over her body

18:17.260 --> 18:21.500
whilst art after looking at her face for an instant despairingly ran out of the room

18:22.360 --> 18:28.400
van helsing whispered to me jonathan is in a stupa such as we know the vampire can produce

18:28.400 --> 18:34.080
we can do nothing with poor madam mina for a few moments till she recovers herself i must wake him

18:35.320 --> 18:41.000
he dipped the end of a towel in cold water and with it began to flick him on the face his wife

18:41.000 --> 18:45.660
all the while holding her face between her hands and sobbing in a way that was heartbreaking to

18:45.660 --> 18:51.720
hear i raised the blind and looked out of the window there was much moonshine and as i looked

18:51.720 --> 18:56.740
i could see quincy morris run across the lawn and hide himself in the shadow of a great yew tree

18:56.740 --> 19:02.620
it puzzled me to think why he was doing this but at the instant i heard harcourt's quick

19:02.620 --> 19:08.220
exclamation as he woke to partial consciousness and turned to the bed on his face as there might

19:08.220 --> 19:13.700
was a look of wild amazement he seemed dazed for a few seconds and then full consciousness seemed

19:13.700 --> 19:19.300
to burst upon him all at once and he started up his wife was aroused by the quick movement

19:19.300 --> 19:24.480
and turned to him with her arms stretched out as though to embrace him instantly however she drew

19:24.480 --> 19:29.560
them in again and putting her elbows together held her hands before her face and shuddered

19:29.560 --> 19:36.600
till the bed beneath her shook in god's name what does this mean harker cried out dr seward dr van

19:36.600 --> 19:42.920
helsing what is it what has happened what is wrong mean it dear what is it and what does that

19:42.920 --> 19:49.500
blood mean my god my god has it come to this and raising himself to his knees he beat his hands

19:49.500 --> 19:56.760
wildly together good god help us help her oh help her with a quick movement he jumped from the bed

19:56.760 --> 20:01.940
and began to pull on his clothes all the man in him awake at the need for instant exertion

20:01.940 --> 20:05.300
what has happened tell me all about it he cried without pausing

20:05.940 --> 20:11.900
dr van helsing you love mina i know oh do something to save her it cannot have gone too far yet

20:11.900 --> 20:17.340
guard her while i look for him his wife through her terror and horror and distress saw some sure

20:17.340 --> 20:22.860
danger to him instantly forgetting her own grief she sees hold of him and cried out no no jonathan

20:22.860 --> 20:27.560
you must not leave me i have suffered enough tonight god knows without the dread of his harming

20:27.560 --> 20:33.040
you must stay with me stay with these friends who will watch over you her expression became

20:33.040 --> 20:38.420
frantic as she spoke and he yielding to her she pulled him down sitting on the bedside

20:38.420 --> 20:44.860
and clung to him fiercely van helsing and i tried to calm them both the professor held up his golden

20:44.860 --> 20:50.800
crucifix and said with wonderful calmness do not fear my dear we are here and whilst this is close

20:50.800 --> 20:56.640
to you no foul thing can approach you are safe for tonight and we must be calm and take counsel together

20:57.900 --> 21:03.420
she shuddered and was silent holding down her head on her husband's breast when she raised it

21:03.420 --> 21:08.080
his white night robe was stained with blood where her lips had touched and where the thin open wound

21:08.080 --> 21:13.560
in the neck had sent forth drops the instant she saw it she drew back with a low wail and whispered

21:13.560 --> 21:20.020
amid the choking sobs unclean unclean i must touch him or kiss him no more but that it should be that

21:20.020 --> 21:26.240
it is i who am now his worst enemy and whom he may have most caused to fear to this he spoke out

21:27.300 --> 21:33.080
nonsense it is a shame to me to hear such a word i would not hear it of you and i shall not hear

21:33.080 --> 21:38.280
it from you may god judge me by my desserts and punish me with more bitter suffering than even

21:38.280 --> 21:44.380
this hour if by any act or will of mine anything ever come between us he put out his arms and

21:44.380 --> 21:50.180
folded her to his breast and for a while she lay there sobbing he looked at us over her bowed head

21:50.180 --> 21:54.940
eyes that blinked amply above his quivering nostrils his mouth was set as steel

21:55.880 --> 22:00.740
